03 - Shell, Console, and Terminal

Shell

  • Shell is the program(s) that provide an interface that allows a user to interact with OS
    • CLI
    • GUI
  • "Login shell" is the program that runs when a user connects to the system (and logs in)
    • When the user quits the login shell (or ends the program), the user is logged out
    • If an administrator terminates a user's login shell the user will get kicked out of the system
      Examples of Shell programs: bash, sh, csh, kshn, zsh, fish

terminal

The terminal is text input and output. Many devices provide a terminal for diagnostics or as a way to provide shell access.
Original terminals were "teletypewriter" devices and in Unix and Linux the basic terminal is called "TTY".

Above image by Jamie - Flickr: Telex machine TTY, CC BY 2.0, https://commons.wikimedia.org/w/index.php?curid=19282428 “… This particular machine was used by a furniture store to order stock…” For a demo see: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=OVdoU-BqFHY

In the current version of the software, a terminal is a software version that is being sent to display, serial port, or network. Here is an example of software tty being displayed on a monitor:

Additionally accessing terminals on some devices may require additional hardware (console) and software (terminal emulator). Examples of terminal emulator software include MobaXterm, PuTTY, and Terminus.

Terminal types

Local terminals include keyboard and screen or console devices such as serial ports, or other management hardware. Local terminals usually require local access to the hardware.

Remote Terminals use network protocols to send and receive text input/output. Examples include Telnet, rlogin, and SSH. Remote terminals are known to a system as virtual (vty) or pseudo-terminal (pty) devices.
Please note that telnet and rlogin are unencrypted and transmitted in plain text. These protocols should not be enabled and used over most networks. The most prevalent (and recommended) protocol for remote terminals on Linux and Unix systems is SSH (secure shell protocol).

SSH features:

  • Encrypted (RSA-Like encryption)
  • server/client identification and verification using signatures (to prevent spoofing)
  • authentication (password or crypto key-based authentication)
  • Server/client architecture, SSH client (ssh) connects to SSH server (sshd)

Since Linux and Unix are multi-user, multiple sessions and multiple users can connect to and use one system at the same time.

Console

Traditionally consoles refer to keyboard and screen hardware. The console is the hardware device, and the terminal is the text displayed in the console.

Above Image by Jason Scott - Flickr: IMG_9976, CC BY 2.0, https://commons.wikimedia.org/w/index.php?curid=29457452
DEC VT100 terminal at the Living Computer Museum connected to the museum's DEC PDP-11/70

Many terminal emulators can emulate the behaviour or properties of various consoles in software. For example, VT100 only displays black and white text on CRT, while xterm256 offers choices of 256 colours for text and text background.

In modern terminology in data centers and enterprise environments, a console is a computer that provides access to the terminal of other systems. Typically these computers run a desktop OS and are used for managing another system. For example, a Hitachi SAN Storage device and an HPE NonStop mainframe contain one or more computers running Windows Desktop that have the required management software for the devices installed, so a locally present and authorized technician can use the console to diagnose, maintain, manage, or repair the attached systems.

Above image: Example of a technician accessing console on an HPE 3PAR SAN storage system
